Name: AGTsupportingCLM
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a claim is supported by one or more arguments via a claim-argument relation.

Name: APEbeeingInSSE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical System Element can be in distinct states.

Name: ASFconformToSTD
Documentation: Specifies, that a SAF Element may be conform to one or more Standards.

Name: Abstract Physical Element
Documentation: Abstract element representing physical structure items keeping properties and relations applicable to all physical items.

Name: Any SAF Element
Documentation: A concept used only together with relational concepts to specify that the relation goes to any other SAF Concept.

Name: Argument
Documentation: An argument is a rule that provides the bridge between what we know or are assuming (sub-claims, evidence) and the claim we are investigating. The argument used depends on the type, trustworthiness and extent of available evidence and the nature of the claim.

Name: Argument Concretion
Documentation: This argument concept is used when a claim needs to be given a more precise definition or interpretation.

Name: Argument Decomposition
Documentation: This argument concept is used to claim that a conclusion about the whole object or property can be deduced from the claims or facts about constituent parts. Decomposition argument blocks can also be used to incorporate defeaters into the case.

Name: Argument Substitution
Documentation: This argument concept is used to claim that if a property holds for one object, then it holds for an equivalent object. Similarly, if a property holds for some object, then an equivalent property will also hold for the same object. The nature of the equivalence will vary with the object and property and will need to be defined.

Name: Aspect
Documentation: Aspects capture a set of characteristics or features of the Entity of Interest in its Environment to address Concerns within an Architecture Description.

Name: CCMcounteringCIM
Documentation: Specifies the fact that any claimable item, e.g., claim, argument, and evidence, is countered by one or more claims.

Name: CFNallocatedToLCE
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that a Context Function is assigned to a Logical Context Element.
Note: This fact may be derived from the Usage of Function of a Context Function allocated to a Logical Context Element.

Name: CLMbeingMadeAboutSBC
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a claim is made about an identified subject matter.

Name: CLMsupportingCIM
Documentation: Specifies the fact that any claimable item, e.g., claim, argument, and evidence, is supported by one or more claims.

Name: CLTmakingCLM
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a claim is made by a defined claimant.

Name: CSTconfirmingSHR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Stakeholder Requirement has certain States of Compliance.

Name: CallowingE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a connection allows Exchange to happen

Name: Category Of Standard
Documentation: Specifies categories in which the standard could be categorized , e.g.,  a data exchange format or a protocol standard, or categories as national, company or international standard.

Name: Claim
Documentation: A claim is a true/false statement about a property of a particular object. A claim is just what you might consider it to be from common usage of the term; an idea that someone is trying to convince somebody else is true. An example claim could be made on a train, e.g., the train is safe.

Name: Claimable Item
Documentation: A claim, argument, and evidence are all types of the abstract concept of a claimable item. This allows a counter-claim to be made about any type of claimable item and a claim to support any type of claimable item.

Name: Claimant
Documentation: A party asserting claims.

Name: Compliance Statement
Documentation:
Used in the communication between Stakeholder (Customer) and Contractor. Compliance Statements are the first answer to the Stakeholder Requirements and are usually together with the Stakeholder Requirements part of the contract. They are valuable input for the System development and System Requirement elicitation. Information status:
* not compliant (with explanation / rationale)
* partially compliant (with explanation / rationale)
* fully compliant

Name: Concern
Documentation: Specifies an information need that a stakeholder of the SAF needs to be satisfied within an MBSE approach using SAF.

Name: Connection
Documentation: Specifies the connection of two interaction points.

Name: Context Function
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that a fundamental action or task is expected to be carried out by an External Entity. 
Note: The intention is to capture the expectations and to explicitly dissect the functionality. This must not be interpreted as an attempt for a behavior specification of an External Entity. Capturing this valuable information is the basis to reach agreement on the functionality at the System boundary by clarifying the expectations about what is performed by Context Elements.

Name: Context Function IN System Process
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Context Function is used in a System Process.

Name: CounterClaim
Documentation: A party's claim is a counter-claim if one party asserts claims in response to the claims of another.

Name: Domain
Documentation: Domain captures viewpoints that belong together within typical SE workflow stages.

Name: EEfromSM
Documentation: Specifies that an exchange comes from a system

Name: EEtoSM
Documentation: Specifies that an exchange goes to a system

Name: EKtypingE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Exchange Kind defines the type of a Exchange.

Name: EKtypingIPP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Exchange Kind defines the type of a Interaction Point Property.

Name: EVCreinforcingAGT
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an argument is reinforced by one or more evidence via a argument-evidence relation.

Name: Evidence
Documentation: An evidence is an artifact that establishes facts that can be trusted and lead directly to a claim. In projects there can many sources of information, but what makes this evidence is the support or rebuttal it gives to a claim.

Name: Exchange
Documentation: Specification for general item exchange (energy, material, information, etc.).

Name: Exchange Kind
Documentation: Specification for a general kind of item (energy, material, information, etc.) to be exchanged.

Name: FRboundedByNFR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Non-Functional Requirement constrains Functional Requirements.

Name: FRrefiningSFN
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Function is refined by Functional Requirements.

Name: Functional Requirement
Documentation: Functional Requirements specify System Functions of the System.

Name: GDcontainingAT
Documentation: Specifies that the grid is composed of several aspects.

Name: GDcontainingDN
Documentation: Specifies that the grid is composed of several domains.

Name: GDcontainingVP
Documentation: Specifies that the grid contains multiple viewpoints

Name: GFEPrelatedToGFUEP
Documentation: specifies that a General Functional Exchange Point is related to a General Function Usage Exchange Point

Name: GFEbeingPartOfGFNU
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Functional Exchange appears within a general Functiona Usage.

Name: GFEfromGFUEP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a General Functional Exchange is coming from a General Functional Usage Exchange Point.

Name: GFEtoGFUEP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a General Functional Exchange is going to a General Functional Usage Exchange Point.

Name: GFNcontrolledAFTER
Documentation: Specifies a sequential execution of Functions.

Name: GFNreceivingINPUT
Documentation: Specifies the Input of a General Function.

Name: GFNsendingOUTPUT
Documentation: Specifies the Output of a General Function.

Name: GFUEPreceivingINPUT
Documentation: Specifies the Input of a Functional Usage.

Name: GFUEPsendingOUTPUT
Documentation: Specifies the Output of a Functional Usage.

Name: GYcontainsTRM
Documentation: specifies that a glossary contains a number of terms. A term is contained only in one glossary.

Name: General Chronological Message
Documentation: Ordered sequential occurrence of exchanges between General Interaction Scenario Participants.

Name: General Context
Documentation: Specifies a General Context.

Name: General Context Element
Documentation: Specifies a General Context Element.

Name: General Context Element Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a General Context Element exists in a given General Context.

Name: General Function
Documentation: Specifies a General Function. It is used as base Class for specific System or Context Functions, or Partial Functions.

Name: General Function Exchange Point
Documentation: A Exchange Point of a Function Usage

Name: General Function Usage Exchange Point
Documentation: A parameter of a System or Context Function.

Name: General Functional Exchange
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an General Functional Exchange between General Function Parameters is taking place.

Name: General Functional Usage
Documentation: Specifies a General Usage of a General Function within  one or more other General Functions.

IsGeneralFor.Name: System Partial Function in System Function

Name: General Interaction Scenario
Documentation: Ordered sequence of exchanges of information, energy, or material between General Interaction Scenario Participants.

Name: General Physical Role
Documentation: General concept of usage of system elements in the context of other system elements on physical level.

Name: General Scenario Participation
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Role participates in a General Interaction Scenario.

Name: Glossary
Documentation: specifies a coherent set of terms.

Name: Goal
Documentation: A Goal is defined as an end state that a Stakeholder intends to achieve. Goals are generally expressed using qualitative words; e.g., “increase”, “improve”, or “easier”. Goals can also be decomposed; e.g., “increase profit” can be decomposed into the Goals “reduce cost” and “increase sales”. However, it is also very common to associate concrete objectives with Goals, which can be used to describe both the quantitative and time-related measures which are essential to describe the desired state, and when it should be achieved.

Name: Grid
Documentation: The grid manages the viewpoints in grid cells assigned to the categories of an domain (row) and an aspect (column).

Name: Hardware Element
Documentation: Pure Hardware Elements. Similarity with the V-Model "hardware unit".

Name: Hardware Element Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a hardware structure comprises hardware elements.

Name: IPDtypingIP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Interaction Point Definition defines the exchange capabilities of an Interaction Point.

Name: IPPisDetailOfIPD
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Interaction Point Property is a detail of an Interaction Point Definition.

Name: Interaction Point
Documentation: Specifies the existence of an interaction point.

Name: Interaction Point Definition
Documentation: Specifies the exchange capabilities of an interaction point on Physical Level.

Name: Interaction Point Property
Documentation: Specifies a detail of an interaction point.

Name: LCEactingInSUC
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Context Element acts in one or more System Use Cases.

Name: LCEperformingCFN
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Context Function is expected to be carried out by the Logical Context Element in this System Context.

Name: LCNallowingLIE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Item Exchange is allowed on the Logical Connection.

Name: LCPboundedByPLS
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Interaction Point is constrained to be implemented on a particular Physical Layer Stack.

Name: LENconceptingPEN
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a logical Environment Entity is a concept for a Physical Environment Entity.

Name: LERspecifyingGPR
Documentation: Specifies that a usage of a Logical Element specifies functions for the usage of a Physical Element.

Name: LESconceptingPES
Documentation: Specifies that the Logical System is a concept for a Physical System.

Name: LETbeeingInSSE
Documentation: Specifies the  System States a Logical Element can be in.

Name: LETimplementingGFN
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that a Logical Element is responsible to implement a System Function.
Note: Logical Elements don't "implement" anything, they pass the function implementation task to Physical Elements.

Name: LETperformingSFN
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Function is expected to be carried out by the SOI in this System Context.

Name: LETspecifyingAPE
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that one or more Logical Element specifies exactly one Physical Element. 
Rationale:
If more than one Physical Element would offer to realize the functionality specified by a Logical Element the responsibility would be ambiguous.
It is okay to assign several Logical Elements to one Physical Element. This means all specified functionality assigned to the Logical Elements is to be implemented by the Physical Element.

Note, that typically the usage of logical elements in a context is mapped to the usage of physical elements in a context (allocation of usage). Thus this relationship between the definitions is derived.

Name: LIEboundedByPL
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Item Exchange is constrained to be implemented on a particular Physical Layer.

Name: LIEboundedByPLS
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Item Exchange is constrained to be implemented on a particular Physical Layer Stack.

Name: LIEimplementsOIE
Documentation: specifies that this exchange in the FD implements (possibly partly) that exchange in the OD

Name: LIPDdefiningDetailOfLIP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Interaction Point Definition defines the exchange capabilities of a Logical Interaction Point.

Name: LIPPspecifyingDetailOfLIPD
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Interaction Point Property is a detail of a Logical Interaction Point Definition.

Name: LIPapplyingToLCE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Interaction Point applies to a Logical Context Element.

Name: LIPapplyingToLET
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Interaction Point applies to a Logical Element.

Name: LIScontainingILCM
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Internal Logical Interaction Scenario contains one or more Internal Logical Chronological Messages.

Name: LURconceptingPUR
Documentation: Specifies that the Logical user is a concept for a Physical User.

Name: Logical Chronological Message
Documentation: Ordered sequential occurrence of exchanges between Logical Interaction Scenario Participants.

Name: Logical Connection
Documentation:
Specifies the connection of two interaction points on Logical Level.
Note: Connections between logical components indicate that item flows are passed from one output of a source component to one or more inputs of target components.

Name: Logical Context Element
Documentation: Represents an abstract element in the given System Context on Logical Level, outside the SOI scope, interacting with the SOI.

Name: Logical Context Element Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Context Element exists in a given Logical System Context.

Name: Logical Context SOI
Documentation: Represents the Logical SOI in the System Context on Logical Level.

Name: Logical Element
Documentation: Describes a conceptual Logical Element as specification for an implementation of a system, or system element.

Name: Logical Element Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a logical element comprises logical elements.

Name: Logical Environment
Documentation: A Logical Environment in the Logical Domain, outside the SOI scope, interacting with the SOI. E.g., air, dirt, sun, road.

Name: Logical External System
Documentation: A Logical External System in the Logical Domain, outside the SOI scope, interacting with the SOI. E.g., power grid, mobile network, fresh water system (in a house).

Name: Logical Interaction Point
Documentation: Specifies the existence of an interaction point on Logical Level.

Name: Logical Interaction Point Definition
Documentation: Specifies the exchange capabilities of an interaction point on Logical Level.

Name: Logical Interaction Point Property
Documentation: Specifies a detail of an interaction point on Logical Level.

Name: Logical Interaction Scenario
Documentation: Ordered sequence of exchanges of information, energy, or material between Logical Interaction Scenario Participants.

Name: Logical Item Exchange
Documentation: Specifies the exchange that is to take place on a connection of two interaction points on Logical Level.

Name: Logical SOI Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Context SOI exists in a given Logical System Context.

Name: Logical Scenario Participation
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Element Role participates in a Logical Interaction Scenario.

Name: Logical System Context
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Context for a System of Interest is defined on Logical Level.

Name: Logical User
Documentation: The Logical User is the representation for a human in the Logical Domain, outside the SOI scope, interacting with the SOI.

Name: Need
Documentation:
A User has a Need in order to reach a certain Goal.
Note: "Buying sugar to bake a birthday cake".

Name: Non-functional Requirement
Documentation: Non-Functional Requirements specify the quality of System Functions, or non-functional requests like legal conformance.

Name: OCNallowingOIE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Item Exchange is allowed on the Operational Connection.

Name: OCYcomposedOF
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Capability consists of other Operational Capabilites.

Name: OCYdependingON
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that an Operational Capability depends on another Operational Capability.

Aliases:
UAF::CapabilityDependency

Name: OCYspecializedBY
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that an Operational Capability is specialized by other Operational Capability. 

Aliases:
UAF::CapabilityGeneralization

Name: OCYsupportingOSY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Story is supported by Operational Capabilities.

Name: ODKcomposedOF
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Domain Kind consists of one or more Operational Domain Kinds.

Name: ODKtypifyingOIE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Domain Kind typifies an Operational Item Exchange.

Name: ODKtypifyingOPE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Domain Kind typifies an Operational Process Exchange.

Name: OIScontainingOCM
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Interaction Scenario contains one or more Operational Chronological Messages.

Name: OISrefiningOSY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Story is refined by one or more Operational Interaction Scenarios.

Name: OPRactingInOSY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Performer acts in an Operational Story.

Name: OPRcapableOFperformingOPS
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that an Operational Performer performs an Operational Activity. Traceability from Operational Activities to Operational Performers is derived via assignment of Operational Action to Operational Roles.

Aliases:
UAF::IsCapableToPerform

Name: OPRcomposedOF
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Performer consists of one or more Operational Performers.

Name: OPRexhibitingOCY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Performer exhibits an Operational Capability under specific environmental conditions.

Name: OPRperformingOPSU
Documentation: Specifies that an Operational Context Role uses an Operational Process in the context of an other Operational Process.

Name: OPSenablingOCY
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that an Operational Process contributes to the provision of one or more Operational Capabilities in the field.

Aliases:
UAF::MapsToCapability

Name: OPSrefiningOSY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Story is refined by one or more Operational Processes.

Name: OSYtakingPlaceInOCT
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that an Operational Story occurs in a certain Operational Context. 
Note: When parts of an Operational Story do occur in several contexts, they shall be duplicated.

Name: Operational Capability
Documentation:
A Operational Capability is a high-level description or specification of an organizational unit's ability to execute a specified course of action, to implement a business process or to provide a service. Operational Capabilities typically require people, processes, infrastructure, technology and supporting systems to be implemented.  A Operational Capability is an enduring element, its implementation may change over time. A necessary or desired change of a Operational Capability triggers the updated of involved systems or the integration new systems.

Aliases:
UAF::Capability
NAF4::Capability

Name: Operational Chronological Message
Documentation: Ordered sequential occurrence of exchanges between Operational Interaction Scenario Participants.

Name: Operational Connection
Documentation:
Specifies the connection between Operational Context Roles in an Operational Context allowing Operational Item Exchange.

Aliases:
UAF::OperationalConnector

Name: Operational Context
Documentation:
An Operational Context is representing a separate Usage Scenario with a specific configuration of Operational Performers, these are interacting in the Scenario exhibiting a specific identified Operational Capability. One or more Operational Contexts meaningful for the Operational Domain are to be identified. 

Aliases:
UAF::HighLevelOperationalConcept

Name: Operational Context Role
Documentation:
An Operational Context Role represents a participant in an Operational context.
It is interacting with other roles of the given Operational Context. Specific characteristics and features or, in case of persons or organizational units, knowledge and skills are assigned to a role necessary for the execution of the performed Operational Processes.

Name: Operational Domain Kind
Documentation: Specifies the kind of Operational Item Exchange between Operational Context Roles or Operational Processes.

Name: Operational Interaction Scenario
Documentation: Ordered sequence of exchanges of information, energy, or material between Operational Interaction Scenario Participants.

Name: Operational Item Exchange
Documentation:
Specifies the Operational Item Exchange that is to take place on an Operational Connection.

Aliases:
UAF::OperationalExchange

Name: Operational Performer
Documentation:
An Operational Performer is an element of the Operational Context that is capable to perform Operational Process Activities contributing to a specific identified Operational Capability. An Operational Performer may be any kind of organization, person, or even a system playing a role in one or more Operational Contexts.

Aliases:
UAF::OperationalPerformer

Name: Operational Process
Documentation:
An Operational Process captures activity-based operational behavior including scenarios, activity actions, and operational exchange flows, e.g., including information, materials, natural resources, etc.

Aliases:
UAF::Operational Activity
NAF::Logical Activity

Name: Operational Process Exchange
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Process has an exchange with another Operational Process.

Name: Operational Process Usage
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that an Operational Process is used in context of another Operational Process.

Aliases:
UAF::OperationalAction

Name: Operational Scenario Participation
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Context Role participates in an Operational Interaction Scenario.

Name: Operational Sketch
Documentation: Specifies a free form sketch depicting a concept.

Name: Operational Story
Documentation: The Operational Story represents one or more Operational Use Cases in the Usage Scenario identified by the Operational Context. The Operational Story is described as narrative story-telling.

Name: PCCapplyingToPCN
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Connector Compatibility Assertion shall apply to a Physical Connection.

Name: PCCassertsCompatibiltyForPCPD
Documentation: Specifies the Physical Interaction Point Definition the Physical Compatibility Assertion is valid for.

Name: PCNallowingPIE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Item Exchange is allowed on the Physical Connection.

Name: PCPOverPCP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a physical interaction point communicates / transfers / flows / over an other physical interaction point. Used to define layered physical interfaces, and show layer relationships between interfaces.

Name: PCPPOverPCPP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a physical interaction point property communicates / transfers / flows / over an other physical interaction point property. Used to define layered physical interfaces, and show layer relationships between interface details.

Name: PCPisPartOfPIPD
Documentation: specifies that a physical interaction point can be a part of a physical interaction point definition. This fosters reuse and allows structuring of definitions.

Name: PEKisAssignedToPL
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Exchange Kind is assigned to a particular Physical Layer.

Name: PEKrealizingSDK
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Domain Kind is realized by Physical Exchange Kinds.

Name: PEKtypingPIE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Exchange Kind defines the type of a Physical Item Exchange.

Name: PEKtypingPIPP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Exchange Kind defines the type of a Physical Interaction Point Property.

Name: PIPDdefiningDetailOfPIP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Interaction Point Definition defines the exchange capabilities of a Physical Interaction  Point.

Name: PIPPspecifyingDetailOfPIPD
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Interaction Point Property is a detail of a Physical Interaction Point Definition.

Name: PIPapplyingToAPE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Interaction Point applies to an Abstract Physical Element.

Name: PIPapplyingToPCE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Interaction Point applies to a Physical Context Element.

Name: PIimplementsSEC
Documentation: specifies that a stereotype from the SAF profile implements a concept

Name: PLOisValidInPLS
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Layer Ordering is valid within a particular Physical Layer Stack.

Name: Physical Connection
Documentation:
Specifies the connection of two physical interaction points.
Note: Connections between physical components indicate that item flows are passed from one output of a source component to one or more inputs of target components.

Name: Physical Connector Compatibility
Documentation: Specifies the fact that two Physical Interaction Point Definitions are compatible and how the Physical Interaction Point Properties are mapped.

Name: Physical Context Element
Documentation: Abstract element of a System Context on Physical Level, outside the SOI scope, interacting with the SOI.

Name: Physical Context Element Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical Context Element exists in a given Physical System Context.

Name: Physical Element
Documentation: A composition of Hardware and Software Elements. Similarity with the V-Model segments and system. See [VXT].

Name: Physical Element Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a physical structure comprises physical elements.

Name: Physical Environment
Documentation: The Physical Environment in the Physical Domain, outside the SOI scope, interacting with the SOI. E.g. air, dirt, sun, road.

Name: Physical Exchange Kind
Documentation: Specification for any kind of physical item (energy, material, information, etc.) to be exchanged on Physical Level. This is the realization of the specification made by System Domain Kinds.

Name: Physical External System
Documentation: The Physical External System in the Physical Domain, outside the SOI scope, interacting with the SOI. E.g. power grid, mobile network, fresh water system (in a house).

Name: Physical Hardware Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a physical structure comprises hardware elements.

Name: Physical Interaction Point
Documentation: Specifies the existence of an interaction point on Physical Level.

Name: Physical Interaction Point Definition
Documentation: Specifies the exchange capabilities of an interaction point on Physical Level.

Name: Physical Interaction Point Property
Documentation: Specifies a detail of an interaction point on Physical Level.

Name: Physical Item Exchange
Documentation: Specifies the exchange that is to take place on a Physical Connection.

Name: Physical Layer
Documentation: Specifies a Physical Layer, usually used for communication.

Name: Physical Layer Ordering
Documentation: Specifies an order among two physical layers. This order is valid within a Physical Layer Stack

Name: Physical Layer Stack
Documentation: Specifies a detail of an interaction point on Physical Level.

Name: Physical SOI
Documentation: Represents the Physical SOI on Physical Level.

Name: Physical SOI Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Physical SOI exists in a given Physical System Context.

Name: Physical Software Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a physical structure comprises software elements.

Name: Physical System Context
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a context for a System of Interest is defined on Physical Level.

Name: Physical User
Documentation: The Physical User is the representation for a human in the physical domain, outside the SOI scope, interacting with the SOI.

Name: Process
Documentation: Unit of Work in Systems Engineering.

Name: RFTmakingCCM
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a counter-claim is made by a defined refuter.

Name: Rationale
Documentation: Specifies why a stakeholder has a concern. Typically that has to do with the work a stakeholder has to do within an MBSE approach.

Name: Refuter
Documentation: A party asserting counter-claims.

Name: SAF Stereotype
Documentation: A stereotype of the SAF Profile Model

Name: SCEactingForOPR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Context Element is acting for the benefit of an Operational Performer.

Name: SCErepresentedBySSH
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Context Element is represented by a SOI Stakeholder.

Name: SCIScontainingLCM
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Context Interaction Scenario contains one or more System Context Chronological Messages.

Name: SCYcomposedOF
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Capability consists of other System Capabilities.

Name: SCYdependingON
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that a System Capability requires another System Capability.

Aliases:
UAF::CapabilityDependency

Name: SCYenablingOCY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Capability integrates System Capabilities to produce a specific outcome to achieve a mission objective.

Name: SCYsatisfyingSHR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Capability satisfies one or more Stakeholder Requirements.

Name: SCYspecializedBY
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that a System Capability is specialized by another System Capability. A CapabilityGeneralization is a taxonomic relationship between a more general Capability and a more specific Capability.

Aliases:
UAF::CapabilityGeneralization

Name: SCYsupportingSUC
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System UseCase is supported by System Capabilities.

Name: SDKbeeingInSSE
Documentation:
Specifies that a System Domain Kind can have certain states.
Note:
Of course an item is in only one distinct state at a certain time. The multiplicity means that an Item can have a set of possible states, and a state can be used to specify possible States for several domain items.

Name: SDKcomposedOF
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Domain Kind consists of one or more System Domain Kinds.

Name: SDKderivingFromODK
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Domain Kind on system level is derived from an Operational Domain Kind.

Name: SDKtypingFPM
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Domain Kind defines the type of a Function Parameter.

Name: SDKtypingLIE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Domain Kind defines the type of a Logical Item Exchange.

Name: SDKtypingLIPP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Domain Kind defines the type of a Logical Interaction Point Property.

Name: SDTcategorizedCOF
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a standard is categorized by one or more categories.

Name: SDTincludingSDT
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a standard is part of another standard.

Name: SDTsupersedingSDT
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a standard supersedes one or more other standards.

Name: SE Concept
Documentation: specifies a SE concept to be supported by SAF

Name: SECisProvidedByVP
Documentation: Specifies, that one or more SE Concepts are provided by the Viewpoints Views

Name: SECrelatesToSEC
Documentation: specifies a relationship of a concept to an other.

Name: SFNallocatedToAPE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a relationship is derived from the assignment of Functions to Logical Elements and the assignment of Logical Elements to Physical Elements.

Name: SFNallocatedToLET
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that a System Function is assigned to a Logical SOI.
Note: This fact may be derived from the Usage of a System Function in a System Process allocated to a Logical Context SOI Role.

Name: SFNboundedByNFR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Non-functional Requirement constrains System Functions.

Name: SFNresultingInSSE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Function can perform a particular set of transitions, resulting in the related target System States.

Name: SFNsupportingSCY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Function supports one or more System Capabilities.

Name: SHRimposedBY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Stakeholder Requirement is provided by Stakeholders.

Name: SHRrefiningCRN
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Stakeholder Concern is refined by Stakeholder Requirements.

Name: SHRrefiningOCY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Capability is refined by Stakeholder Requirements.

Name: SHRrefiningOSY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an Operational Story is refined by Stakeholder Requirements.

Name: SMhavingGF
Documentation: Specifies, that a system has general functions.

Name: SMhavingIP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System has one or more Interaction Points.

Name: SOIactingForOPR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a SOI is acting for the benefit of an Operational Performer.

Name: SPFNallocatedToAPE
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that a System Partial Function is assigned to an Abstract Physical Element.
Note: This fact may be derived from the Usage of Function of a System Partial Function allocated to a Physical SOI Element Role

Name: SPFNallocatedToLET
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that a System Partial Function is assigned to a Logical SOI Element.
Note: This fact may be derived from the Usage of Function of a System Partial Function allocated to a Internal Logical Element Role

Name: SPSenablingOPS
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Process enables the accomplishment of an Operational Process.

Name: SPSenablingSCY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Process contributes to the provision of one or more System Capabilities in the field.

Name: SPSrefiningSUC
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Use Case is refined by one System Process.

Name: SRderivingFromSR
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that System Requirements are derived from a Stakeholder Requirement. 
Note: This is the relationship of requirements of different architectural levels. When the team responsible for the subsystem has direct access to the full upstream requirements set, then no subcontractor relationship needs to be established.

Name: SRderivingFromSTKR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Requirement is derived from a Stakeholder Requirement. Note: It may be used in a customer supplier relationship situation and supports the V Model concept of "External Unit Specification". See [VXT].

Name: SRrefiningLICP
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Logical Interaction Point is refined by System Requirements.

Name: SRrefiningSCY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Capability is refined by System Requirements.

Name: SRrefiningSUC
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Use Case is refined by System Requirements.

Name: SSEperformingSFN
Documentation: Specifies the fact that the Function is only provided in distinct States. The state is a precondition for the Function to be able to perform.

Name: SSHhavingCRN
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Stakeholder has certain Concerns.

Name: SSHrelatedToSSH
Documentation: Explains relations between the Stakeholders of the System and other relevant System parties. It helps to understand the Stakeholder community and to approach the right point of contact for clarification of project relevant issues.

Name: SSHrepresentingOPR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a SOI Stakeholder is representing an Operational Performer.

Name: SSHrepresentingUSR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that an User is represented by Stakeholders.

Name: SSTimplementsVP
Documentation:
specifies, that one ore more SAF Stereotypes implement a viewpoint.
Note: Multiple Stereotypes are used if there are alternate presentations.

Name: STDcontainsGY
Documentation: specifies that a standard may contain one or more glossaries.

Name: STDissuedBySTO
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a standard is issued by an organization of standardization.

Name: SUCenablingOSY
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Use Case enables the realization of an Operational Story.

Name: SUChasPostConditionSSE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Use Case has a state as Postcondition.

Name: SUChasPreConditionSSE
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Use Case has a state as Precondition.

Name: SUCincludingSUC
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Use Case includes other System Use Cases. The included use case is then no longer a full System Use Case, but a partial System Use Case.

Name: SUCrefiningSHR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Stakeholder Requirement is refined by System Use Cases.

Name: SUCsynthesizingCFN
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that a Context Function is used in a System Use Case, e.g., as a Trigger, Action, or Task.
Note: This is a derived relationship.

Name: SUCsynthesizingSFN
Documentation:
Specifies the fact that a System Function is used in a System Use Case, e.g., as a Trigger, Action, or Task. 
Note: This is a derived relationship.

Name: SUCtakingPlaceInLSC
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Use Case takes place in a Logical System Context.

Name: Software Element
Documentation: Pure Software Elements. Similarity with the V-Model "software unit".

Name: Software Element Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a software structure comprises software elements.

Name: Stakeholder
Documentation: specifies someone (typically a role) having an information need within an MBSE approach.

Name: Stakeholder Requirement
Documentation: A Stakeholder Requirement is a Requirement imposed by a Stakeholder. Stakeholder Concerns are refined by Stakeholder Requirements applicable for the SOI. The Stakeholder Requirements are a result of discussions and agreements of how the SOI addresses the Concerns of the respective Stakeholder.

Name: Standard
Documentation: Specifies a standard which shall potentially be complied by the system or a part of the system.

Name: Standardization Organization
Documentation: An organization of standardization, e.g., International Organization for Standardization (ISO), Object Management Group (OMG), etc.

Name: State Transition
Documentation: Describes an allowed transition between two states of an item that can be in distinct States.

Name: Subject of Claim
Documentation: Note: A claim cannot be generic, it has to be about something, it has to have a defined subject, e.g., system safety.

Name: SysML Stereotype
Documentation: A stereotype from sysml

Name: System
Documentation: An abstract element representing a System.

Name: System Capability
Documentation:
1) A System Capability is an operation or task that performs an action to produce a specific performance-based outcome. NOTE that a system capability represents the potential to perform an action. In contrast, an operational capability may integrate several physical system capabilities to produce a specific outcome to achieve a mission objective. [Wasson2006, SystemAnalysis+Design+Development]
2) System Capabilities, as system assets, characterize the mechanical, electrical, optical, or processing features that enable a system to function, process mission resources, make decisions, and achieve a required level of success based on performance. A system capability is broader in scope than simply a functional element (and performance bounding elements), especially in large, complex ecosystems. It represents a physical potential - strength, ability, endurance - to perform an outcome-based action for a given duration under a specified set of operating environment conditions. [Wasson2006, SystemAnalysis+Design+Development]

Aliases:
UAF::Capability
NAF4::Capability

Name: System Context
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a context for a System of Interest is defined.

Name: System Context Chronological Message
Documentation: Ordered sequential occurrence of exchanges between System Context Interaction Scenario Participants.

Name: System Context Element
Documentation: An abstract element representing a System Context Element. Base class for specific kinds of Context Elements.

Name: System Context Element Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Context Element exists in a given System Context.

Name: System Context Interaction Scenario
Documentation: Ordered sequence of exchanges of information, energy, or material between System Context Interaction Scenario Participants.

Name: System Context Role
Documentation: General role of a Logical System Context.

Name: System Context Scenario Participation
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Context Role participates in a System Context Interaction Scenario.

Name: System Domain Kind
Documentation: Specification for any kind of conceptual item (energy, material, information, etc.) to be exchanged on Functional or Logical Level. The System Domain Kind is agnostic to any realization on Physical Level.

Name: System Function
Documentation:
Specifies the fundamental action or task that have to take place in the System in accepting and processing the
inputs and in processing and generating the outputs.
A System Function
 * accepts input from the System boundary 
 * exposes its output at the System boundary
 * changes the System's State
 * is dependent on System's State
Note: A System Function does not need to expose observable output, when it changes the System's state in a way that is observable by other system functions. Furthermore, a System Function does not need to accept any input from the system boundary, when it is dependent on the System State, which in turn is changeable by other System Functions.

Name: System Function IN System Process
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Function is used in a System Process.

Name: System Of Interest
Documentation: An abstract element representing a SOI. Base class for specific kinds of SOIs.

Name: System Partial Function
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Partial Function is a decomposed part of a System Function and defines details of the System Function it belongs to.

Name: System Partial Function in System Function
Documentation: Specifies that a System Partial Function is used in a system function

Name: System Process
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System Process captures system behavior as a specific sequence of actions or tasks, and system exchanges including information, materials, energy, etc.

Name: System Requirement
Documentation: System Requirements specify System Functions, non-functional properties, or constraints of the System.

Name: System Role
Documentation: Specifies, that a system is part of a system.

Name: System SOI Role
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a System SOI exists in a given System Context.

Name: System State
Documentation: Describes a state (or mode) of something that can have distinct states.

Name: System Use Case
Documentation:
The System Use Cases are a table of content of the services provided by the System of Interest to its System Actors. A System Use Case is only the abstract of the depicted System behavior and represents the purpose. While the main System of Interest interaction actors participating in this Use Case are identified, the behavior itself is specified by a Use Case Activity, 
Note: The intended use (and also misuse in so called "black use cases") of the System of Interest is captured in free text; story telling at a coarse level of detail which is understandable to Customers (non engineering stakeholders in general).

Name: System of Interest Concern
Documentation:
Any kind of interest a Stakeholder has. 
Note: Redundant with the meaning of "Need"?

Name: System of Interest Stakeholder
Documentation:
An individual, team, or organization (or classes thereof) with interests in, or concerns relative to, a system. It may be involved in any life cycle phase of the System. The Stakeholder represents a class or kind of Stakeholders. Stakeholders have a certain involvement: Stakeholder Involvement captures the influence of a project specific Stakeholder on the System. Stakeholder Involvement is characterized by
* Contact Person
* Kind of involvement
* Life Cycle Phases involved
* Relevance decision if and up to which degree Stakeholder is considered
* Rationale for decision when Stakeholder is not considered

Name: TRMdefinedBySDT
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a term is defined by a standard.

Name: Term
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a term is usually defined by a standard, but can also be defined as part of system development work.

Name: UML Metaclass
Documentation: A metaclass from UML

Name: USAGEallocatedTo
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Usage of Function is allocated to a Usage of System Element.

Name: User
Documentation:
Representation for a human in the Logical Domain, outside the SOI scope, interacting with the SOI.
Note: This seems to be highly redundant with definition of "Role".

Name: VPbelongingToAT
Documentation: specifies that a viewpoint belongs to one aspect.

Name: VPbelongingToDN
Documentation: specifies that a viewpoint belongs to one domain.

Name: VPframesCN
Documentation: Specifies that a Viewpoint frames one or more concerns. That means that the views conform to that viewpoint satisfy the information need expressed by the concerns.

Name: VWconformingToVP
Documentation: specifies that a view conforms to a viewpoint.

Name: View
Documentation: A architecture view comprises portion of an architecture description and addresses information-relevant concerns framed by a architecture viewpoint.

Name: Viewpoint
Documentation: A architecture viewpoint defines set of conventions for the creation, interpretation and use of an architecture view to frame one or more concerns

Name: controlledAFTER
Documentation: Specifies the sequencing of Operational Processes in time.

Name: satisfyingSHR
Documentation: Specifies the fact that a Stakeholder Requirement is satisfied by SAF Model Elements.
